## Executive Summary

Our U.S. pharmaceutical firm expects to receive an **€8,000,000 EUR-denominated payment in one year**. At today's spot rate of **1.1608 USD/EUR**, that receivable is worth approximately **$9.29M USD** — but the 1-year forward market prices EUR at only **1.0890**, implying a ~6.2% depreciation and roughly **$568K in potential lost proceeds** if we remain unhedged. EUR/USD has already swung between 1.1453 and 1.2019 in 2026 alone, reflecting diverging Fed and ECB policy paths. This memo frames the exposure, outlines three hedging strategies, and maps the analytical work ahead in Stages 2–4.

---

## Background & Objectives

**The Exposure — Scenario 2: U.S. Pharmaceutical Exporter**

| Parameter | Value |
|---|---|
| Receivable | $8,000,000 USD-equivalent, payable in EUR |
| Horizon | 1 year from April 1, 2026 |
| Spot Rate (K) | 1.1608 USD/EUR (Yahoo Finance, April 1, 2026) |
| 1-Year Forward Rate | 1.0890 USD/EUR |
| USD Interest Rate | 3.625% (Fed target midpoint, held March 2026) |
| EUR Interest Rate | 2.00% (ECB deposit facility, held March 2026) |

**Why it's risky:** The forward rate sits 6.2% below spot — the market is already pricing in meaningful EUR weakness. If our receivable settles near the forward rate instead of today's spot, we lose approximately $568K in USD proceeds before any further adverse move. Tail risk is elevated: the ECB faces ~26% market odds of a rate hike in April 2026 (Polymarket, March 31, 2026), adding volatility to EUR direction. An unhedged position exposes revenue targets and financial reporting to exchange rate outcomes entirely outside management's control.

**Primary objective:** Evaluate whether and how to lock in or protect a portion of the USD value of this receivable before settlement.

---

## Methods

Three hedging instrument families will be evaluated against the unhedged baseline:

**1. Forward Contract** — Lock the rate today at **1.0890** for delivery in one year.
- ✅ Full certainty; proceeds are known and budgetable.
- ❌ No upside if EUR strengthens; creates a binding obligation.

**2. EUR Put Option (Protective Floor)** — Buy the right to sell EUR at **K = 1.1608**, premium **$0.021/EUR**.
- ✅ Floors downside; full upside retained if EUR appreciates.
- ❌ Premium cost reduces net proceeds regardless of outcome.

**3. EUR Call Option / Collar** — Buy or write EUR calls at **K = 1.1608**, premium **$0.026/EUR**; can be paired with the put to build a zero-cost collar.
- ✅ Writing the call offsets put premium, reducing net hedging cost.
- ❌ Writing a call caps USD upside above the strike.

Stage 2 will model all three strategies plus the unhedged baseline across a terminal EUR/USD range of approximately 0.95–1.30, computing net USD proceeds and break-even rates for each approach.

